<div id="comment_244586921" class="brown_comment">
  <div class="xhr_comment_photo">
    	<a alt="Rick Dutkiewicz" href="/user/show/50951370-rick-dutkiewicz"><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451759608p1/50951370.jpg" alt="50951370" /></a>
  </div>
  <div class="xhr_comment_body">
    <a style="font-weight:bold" href="/user/show/50951370-rick-dutkiewicz">Rick Dutkiewicz</a>

      
<span id="freeTextContainer16045139538115319710">[SPOILER ALERT!] People who are complaining that Rowan had a personality change right at the end of the book aren&apos;t looking very closely at what has b</span>
  <span id="freeText16045139538115319710" style="display:none">[SPOILER ALERT!] People who are complaining that Rowan had a personality change right at the end of the book aren't looking very closely at what has been described throughout the book (and continued in the Lasher book). The spirit has been honing his ability to control his witches for many generations, and has inbred the family to help breed the most powerful but easily manipulated witches for his purposes. You could say that she was possessed; that's a good way to think about it. But a lot more was included, specifically the smells, the sub-conscious as well as explicit suggestions and manipulations that Lasher wove. He preyed on Rowan's personality traits, her pride, her interest in science, her longing for family ties, etc. etc. The story is deep and doesn't deserve a quick dismissal because some readers didn't retain or imagine just how deeply Lasher was controlling the entire scenario.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16045139538115319710" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

    <br/>

    <span class="xhrCommentFooter greyText">
      Feb 01, 2022 08:20PM
